# Session memory is append-only and chronologically ordered, and every entry
# shares the same line-identical `topics:`/`related_entries:` scaffolding. That
# makes git's line-based three-way merge actively dangerous here: it anchors on
# the shared lines, treats them as agreed content, and splices one entry's body
# into another while stranding a YAML fence - a silent corruption, not a
# conflict. `-merge` makes concurrent edits conflict wholesale instead, so the
# structural merge (`session merge-branch`, which rebuilds the file from parsed
# entry records) is the only way through. The tool itself is unaffected: it
# already resets branch-touched session files to base content before fusing.
.memory-seed/sessions/** -merge
